JACK2 on Haiku
==============

This is a native port of JACK2 (jackd2), the low-latency audio server, to Haiku,
including a new Media Kit based audio backend. It is a real port of the JACK
engine (graph, transport, multi-client, libjack) running on Haiku, not an
API-emulation shim.


Status
------

Built and running on Haiku R1/beta5 x86_64 (developed against current Haiku,
tested both in a QEMU/KVM VM and on bare-metal hardware):

- The portable engine, libjack/libjackserver, and the POSIX IPC layer
  (threads, semaphores, shared memory, sockets, FIFOs) build and run.
- "jackd -d dummy" starts, accepts clients, and shuts down cleanly.
- The standard JACK example tools (jack_lsp, jack_metro, jack_connect,
  jack_iodelay, ...) connect and run.
- Three audio backends are available:
    dummy   - no hardware; for testing the engine and IPC.
    haiku   - BSoundPlayer; routed through the system mixer; stereo; the
              simplest audible path.
    hmulti  - direct /dev/audio/hmulti access; low latency, multi-channel,
              full-duplex; the primary target.
- On real HD Audio hardware, "jackd -d hmulti" runs full-duplex at a 128-frame
  period (48 kHz). Audible output and playback+capture ports are confirmed, and
  the device buffer size is honored for low latency.


Building
--------

Install the build prerequisites with pkgman:

    pkgman install -y gcc make pkgconfig mpc mpfr haiku_devel

A minimal Haiku install lacks these: mpc and mpfr are required by the compiler
(cc1plus links against libmpc/libmpfr), and haiku_devel provides the POSIX/OS
development headers. Installing haiku_devel pulls a matching base-system update
and requires a reboot to activate.

Configure, build, and install into the Haiku non-packaged tree:

    python3 ./waf configure --prefix=/boot/system/non-packaged
    python3 ./waf build
    python3 ./waf install

Invoke waf as "python3 ./waf": Haiku ships python3, and the waf shebang's plain
"python" is not present. Installing under /boot/system/non-packaged puts jackd and
the tools on PATH, libjack on the default library search path, and the backend
add-ons where jackd looks for them, so no JACK_DRIVER_DIR or LIBRARY_PATH tweaks
are needed to run from the install tree.

libsamplerate and libsndfile are optional and not required for the core server.


Running
-------

    jackd -d hmulti -r 48000 -p 128

Ports appear as system:capture_1/2 and system:playback_1/2. Connect clients with
the usual tools, e.g.:

    jack_metro --bpm 120 &
    jack_connect metro:120_bpm system:playback_1
    jack_connect metro:120_bpm system:playback_2

Backend selection:

    jackd -d hmulti   # hmulti_audio, low latency (recommended)
    jackd -d haiku    # BSoundPlayer, through the system mixer
    jackd -d dummy    # no hardware


Media server handoff
--------------------

Haiku's media_server normally owns the audio hardware. When jackd opens the
hmulti device and finds it busy, the hmulti backend automatically stops the media
services (the same operation as "Restart Media Services" in Media preferences),
takes exclusive control of the device, and restarts the media services when jackd
exits.

While JACK owns the card, Haiku's Media preferences mixer shows the output as not
connected. This is expected: JACK holds the raw device, exactly as it does with
ALSA on Linux. Any hardware mixer setup (input source, capture gain) must be done
in Media preferences while jackd is not running; those codec settings persist when
jackd takes the device.


Known limitations
-----------------

- USB audio interfaces that use USB Audio Class 2.0 exposed as an Interface
  Association Descriptor (device class 0xef) - which is how virtually all modern
  class-compliant interfaces present - are not usable. Haiku's usb_audio kernel
  driver enumerates them on the USB bus (they appear in listusb) but does not
  publish an hmulti device node for them, so neither JACK nor the rest of the
  system can use them. Confirmed with a Behringer UMC204HD (1397:0508) and an
  XMOS-based NUX USB Audio 2.0 (20b1:2018). This is a limitation of Haiku's
  usb_audio driver, not of this port; only the built-in HD Audio codec is usable
  until that driver is extended. Extending usb_audio for UAC2/IAD devices is
  tracked as future work.

- Measuring round-trip latency with jack_iodelay requires a working analog
  loopback (an output physically wired back to an input). On the built-in HDA
  codec this depends on which physical output and input the codec has active,
  configured through Media preferences. It is unrelated to the JACK backend.


